{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DZ2V2ut4ftAVuZkXb1vznc","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package protocol\n     2→\n     3→import (\n     4→\t\"bytes\"\n     5→\t\"encoding/json\"\n     6→\t\"fmt\"\n     7→\t\"io\"\n     8→\t\"time\"\n     9→)\n    10→\n    11→type MessageType string\n    12→\n    13→const (\n    14→\tMsgStepStarted  MessageType = \"step_started\"\n    15→\tMsgStepCompleted MessageType = \"step_completed\"\n    16→\tMsgRunCompleted  MessageType = \"run_completed\"\n    17→\tMsgRunTitle      MessageType = \"run_title\"\n    18→\tMsgLog           MessageType = \"log\"\n    19→\tMsgError         MessageType = \"error\"\n    20→)\n    21→\n    22→type StatusMessage struct {\n    23→\tType      MessageType `json:\"type\"`\n    24→\tStepName  string      `json:\"step_name,omitempty\"`\n    25→\tResult    string      `json:\"result,omitempty\"`\n    26→\tMessage   string      `json:\"message,omitempty\"`\n    27→\tTimestamp time.Time   `json:\"timestamp\"`\n    28→}\n    29→\n    30→// flusher is an optional interface for writers that support explicit flushing.\n    31→type flusher interface {\n    32→\tFlush() error\n    33→}\n    34→\n    35→type StatusWriter struct {\n    36→\tw   io.Writer\n    37→\tenc *json.Encoder\n    38→}\n    39→\n    40→func NewStatusWriter(w io.Writer) *StatusWriter {\n    41→\treturn &StatusWriter{w: w, enc: json.NewEncoder(w)}\n    42→}\n    43→\n    44→func (s *StatusWriter) StepStarted(stepName string) {\n    45→\ts.write(StatusMessage{Type: MsgStepStarted, StepName: stepName})\n    46→}\n    47→\n    48→func (s *StatusWriter) StepCompleted(stepName, result string) {\n    49→\ts.write(StatusMessage{Type: MsgStepCompleted, StepName: stepName, Result: result})\n    50→}\n    51→\n    52→func (s *StatusWriter) RunCompleted(result string) {\n    53→\ts.write(StatusMessage{Type: MsgRunCompleted, Result: result})\n    54→}\n    55→\n    56→func (s *StatusWriter) RunTitle(title string) {\n    57→\ts.write(StatusMessage{Type: MsgRunTitle, Message: title})\n    58→}\n    59→\n    60→func (s *StatusWriter) Log(stepName, message string) {\n    61→\ts.write(StatusMessage{Type: MsgLog, StepName: stepName, Message: message})\n    62→}\n    63→\n    64→func (s *StatusWriter) Error(stepName, message string) {\n    65→\ts.write(StatusMessage{Type: MsgError, StepName: stepName, Message: message})\n    66→}\n    67→\n    68→func (s *StatusWriter) write(msg StatusMessage) {\n    69→\tmsg.Timestamp = time.Now()\n    70→\t_ = s.enc.Encode(msg)\n    71→\t// Flush the underlying writer if it supports it, to ensure real-time delivery.\n    72→\tif f, ok := s.w.(flusher); ok {\n    73→\t\t_ = f.Flush()\n    74→\t}\n    75→}\n    76→\n    77→func ParseStatusStream(data []byte) ([]StatusMessage, error) {\n    78→\tvar msgs []StatusMessage\n    79→\tdec := json.NewDecoder(bytes.NewReader(data))\n    80→\tfor dec.More() {\n    81→\t\tvar msg StatusMessage\n    82→\t\tif err := dec.Decode(&msg); err != nil {\n    83→\t\t\treturn msgs, fmt.Errorf(\"failed to decode status message: %w\", err)\n    84→\t\t}\n    85→\t\tmsgs = append(msgs, msg)\n    86→\t}\n    87→\treturn msgs, nil\n    88→}\n    89→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3b83d887-9f3b-4385-8c16-91cb9c40f66f","uuid":"b6147224-d5a3-451f-8e4b-b3161d1c0f3a","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/internal/protocol/status.go","content":"package protocol\n\nimport (\n\t\"bytes\"\n\t\"encoding/json\"\n\t\"fmt\"\n\t\"io\"\n\t\"time\"\n)\n\ntype MessageType string\n\nconst (\n\tMsgStepStarted  MessageType = \"step_started\"\n\tMsgStepCompleted MessageType = \"step_completed\"\n\tMsgRunCompleted  MessageType = \"run_completed\"\n\tMsgRunTitle      MessageType = \"run_title\"\n\tMsgLog           MessageType = \"log\"\n\tMsgError         MessageType = \"error\"\n)\n\ntype StatusMessage struct {\n\tType      MessageType `json:\"type\"`\n\tStepName  string      `json:\"step_name,omitempty\"`\n\tResult    string      `json:\"result,omitempty\"`\n\tMessage   string      `json:\"message,omitempty\"`\n\tTimestamp time.Time   `json:\"timestamp\"`\n}\n\n// flusher is an optional interface for writers that support explicit flushing.\ntype flusher interface {\n\tFlush() error\n}\n\ntype StatusWriter struct {\n\tw   io.Writer\n\tenc *json.Encoder\n}\n\nfunc NewStatusWriter(w io.Writer) *StatusWriter {\n\treturn &StatusWriter{w: w, enc: json.NewEncoder(w)}\n}\n\nfunc (s *StatusWriter) StepStarted(stepName string) {\n\ts.write(StatusMessage{Type: MsgStepStarted, StepName: stepName})\n}\n\nfunc (s *StatusWriter) StepCompleted(stepName, result string) {\n\ts.write(StatusMessage{Type: MsgStepCompleted, StepName: stepName, Result: result})\n}\n\nfunc (s *StatusWriter) RunCompleted(result string) {\n\ts.write(StatusMessage{Type: MsgRunCompleted, Result: result})\n}\n\nfunc (s *StatusWriter) RunTitle(title string) {\n\ts.write(StatusMessage{Type: MsgRunTitle, Message: title})\n}\n\nfunc (s *StatusWriter) Log(stepName, message string) {\n\ts.write(StatusMessage{Type: MsgLog, StepName: stepName, Message: message})\n}\n\nfunc (s *StatusWriter) Error(stepName, message string) {\n\ts.write(StatusMessage{Type: MsgError, StepName: stepName, Message: message})\n}\n\nfunc (s *StatusWriter) write(msg StatusMessage) {\n\tmsg.Timestamp = time.Now()\n\t_ = s.enc.Encode(msg)\n\t// Flush the underlying writer if it supports it, to ensure real-time delivery.\n\tif f, ok := s.w.(flusher); ok {\n\t\t_ = f.Flush()\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc ParseStatusStream(data []byte) ([]StatusMessage, error) {\n\tvar msgs []StatusMessage\n\tdec := json.NewDecoder(bytes.NewReader(data))\n\tfor dec.More() {\n\t\tvar msg StatusMessage\n\t\tif err := dec.Decode(&msg); err != nil {\n\t\t\treturn msgs, fmt.Errorf(\"failed to decode status message: %w\", err)\n\t\t}\n\t\tmsgs = append(msgs, msg)\n\t}\n\treturn msgs, nil\n}\n","numLines":89,"startLine":1,"totalLines":89}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014XnUvYfwmNdW7kDaAVpvGN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me trace the two main failure paths:\n\n### Container runs (gRPC server - `server.go`)\n\nWhen the agent (in-container) experiences a step failure:\n1. The engine returns an error like `\"step %q execution failed: %w\"` \n2. The agent runner (`agent/runner.go` line 97-103) calls:\n   - `statusWriter.Error(\"\", runErr.Error())` - sends an `MsgError` with the error message (but empty step name!)\n   - `statusWriter.RunCompleted(\"failed\")` - sends `MsgRunCompleted` with \"failed\" result\n\n\n3. The server's `trackRun` method completely ignores `MsgError` messages in its switch statement, so they're discarded\n4. When `MsgRunCompleted` arrives with \"failed\", that result gets captured, but during finalization the run is marked as failed without ever setting an error message\n\nSo the error information from the agent is lost entirely for container runs—the `MsgError` is dropped and no error details make it into the final run state.\n\nFor host runs, the situation is different: when a step fails, the error message gets properly set via the `Fail()` method, so users actually see what went wrong.\n\nThe fix is straightforward—the server needs to handle `MsgError` messages and store them so they can be attached to the run when it completes, matching what host runs already do.\n\nLooking at how errors flow through the agent, I notice the engine generates structured error messages like `\"step \\\"develop\\\" execution failed: exit status 1\"`, but when the agent sends these via the protocol, it's passing the full error string without preserving the step context separately. The engine itself has different error types it can produce—step execution failures, undeclared result errors, and others—so there's room to make the error handling more structured across both paths.\n\nMy approach is to leverage the fact that the engine error already contains the step name embedded in its message, so the daemon can extract what it needs from there. In the agent, I'll make sure the error message gets properly captured, and then in the server's `trackRun` function, I'll handle the `MsgError` messages to extract and store that error information. the error message is already embedded in `MsgError`, so I just need to capture it in `trackRun` and use it when setting the final run state. I could also examine the `Run.StepExecutions` to identify which step failed, but the error message itself already contains that context. The simplest approach is to handle `MsgError` in `trackRun`, store the error text, and pass it to `run.Fail()` when the run completes with a failure status. Looking at the abort case in the host runner, when a step is aborted the run gets marked as failed but no error message is set, which is fine since it's an intentional abort. The real problem is capturing error messages when a step actually fails. My plan is to handle `MsgError` messages in `trackRun` to grab the error text, then use that when finalizing failed runs, and fall back to deriving the error from step executions if needed.\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. The engine already sends informative error messages like \"step \\\"develop\\\" execution failed: exit code 1\" as `MsgError` messages, so I just need the server to capture and use those instead of ignoring them.\n\nFor cases where a step produces a \"fail\" result without an explicit error message, I'll need to extract the step name and error details from the step executions themselves, since `MsgError.StepName` isn't currently populated. the engine always returns a `run` object even on failure, so I can inspect `run.StepExecutions` to find which step failed. I need to set the step name properly when calling `Error()` and then handle `MsgError` on the server side to extract both the step name and error message.\n\nWriting error handling logic... I'm looking at how the host runner handles step failures that don't produce engine errors—like when a step returns \"fail\" and routes to \"abort\", which sets the aborted flag and completes the run without an error object. In that scenario, I need to check what happens in the host runner when `runErr` is nil. I'm tracing through two failure paths: when a step execution returns an error directly, the engine captures it and passes it along, but when a step returns a \"fail\" result that triggers an abort, there's no error message attached. I also need to understand what happens with the \"no branches reached done\" error—the engine returns it but I'm not sure how it flows through to the error message field.\n\nLooking at the agent runner code, when the engine returns an error, it gets sent directly through the status writer, so that path is clear. The key insight is that different error types follow the same general pattern: the engine either returns an error directly, or the error needs to be derived from the step execution results. The engine can return a nil run if workflow validation fails early, so I need to handle that case in the implementation. Looking at the completion logic, when a run is aborted, it's marked as failed, and I need to trace through whether `runErr` gets set properly in that scenario.\n\nI'm considering whether to enhance the engine to set an error message directly on the run object rather than just returning it as a Go error—that way both the agent and host paths would automatically capture the error message without needing separate handling.\n\nHowever, that would require changing the engine's behavior, and the host runner already works fine with the current approach where it captures the Go error string. For the host path, the error message from the engine already includes the step name (like `step \"develop\" execution failed: exit status 1`), so it's already providing the key information needed. I'll stick with having the agent send better error info via MsgError that the server can use for the ErrorMessage field. The core issue is that when steps fail with errors, that information isn't surfaced to users, forcing them to dig through logs to understand what went wrong. The abort case is related but secondary—when a step returns \"fail\" and triggers an abort, the run just shows as failed with no context. Let me focus on capturing actual execution errors first, then I can look at how the `Fail()` method sets error messages versus `Complete()`.\n\nThe real challenge is that the engine operates on a local run object separate from the persisted one, so even if the engine captures errors, they won't automatically flow to the stored run that users see.\n\nFor the host runner, it already copies errors from the engine result to the persisted run. But for the agent, the engine's run is ephemeral and never persisted—the agent needs to explicitly send error details to the daemon through status messages.\n\nSo the fix involves updating the agent runner to extract the failed step name from the engine's run and include it in the error message it sends, while the gRPC server needs to handle these enriched error messages when updating the persisted run.\n\nFor the host runner's abort case, I can examine the step executions on the persisted run to identify which step failed and set an appropriate error message.\n\nIn the \"no branches reached done\" scenario, the engine first marks the run as failed, then returns an error describing the workflow issue—I need to capture both pieces of information.\n\nNow let me start implementing these changes, but I should first verify what other aspects I might be overlooking.\n\nChecking for existing tests...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4799,"cache_read_input_tokens":33828,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4799},"output_